ce:section.ce:para:
The PL emission of the NB-CQDs can be quenched by DA. Fig. 7
                        A shows that the PL emission intensity of the NB-CQDs at 490 nm gradually decreased with increasing DA concentration. Fig. 7B shows a good linear correlation (R2 = 0.9958) for PL emission intensity versus DA concentration over a wide range of 0.1–70 μM, giving a linear regression equation of F = 7577.0380 − 49.2325 × [DA concentration]. The LOD of DA was 11 nM, with a signal-to-noise ratio of 3. The NB-CQDs provided a better linear detection range and lower LOD than those of reported CQD-based probes for detecting DA (Table 1
                        ). Furthermore, the current NB-CQD-based PL sensor did not require compositing with other materials, which represented a significant advantage compared with reported sensors. The PL response of the NB-CQD solution was measured in the presence various small organic molecules, to investigate the selectivity for DA. The NB-CQDs showed good selectivity, and the PL quenching effect was strongest in the presence of DA, as shown in Fig. 7C.

Then, a possible DA detection mechanism was investigated. The two typical mechanisms of PL quenching are dynamic and static quenching. Dynamic quenching involves the diffusion-related interaction between the quencher and excited-state fluorescent molecule. Static quenching involves the formation of a complex between the quencher and ground-state fluorescent molecule. Dynamic and static quenching can be described by the Stern-Volmer equation:

                              for dynamic quenching, F0/F = KSV [Q] + 1,




                              for static quenching, F0/F = 1 + Kq [Q],

                        where KSV is the Stern-Volmer quenching constant, Kq is the binding constant of the complex, [Q] is the DA concentration, and F0 and F are the PL intensities of the NB-CQDs at 490 nm in the absence and presence of DA, respectively. Fig. 7A shows a linear relationship between F0/F and DA concentration over the range of 0.1–70 μM (R2 = 0.9689). The PL lifetime of the NB-CQDs was 10.5 ns, as shown in Fig. 8
                        A. The formula Kqτ0 = Ksv yielded a bimolecular annihilation constant (Kq) of 1.18 × 1012 L·mol−1·s−1, i.e. approximately 1012. Thus, Kq was larger than the typical quenching constant for fluorescent molecules of (1.0–2.0) × 1010 L·mol−1·s−1. This suggested that quenching occurred via a static quenching mechanism. In addition, UV–vis absorption spectra of the NB-CQDs were recorded in the presence of various DA concentrations, as shown in Fig. 8B. The absorption peak of the NB-CQDs at 240 nm gradually disappeared upon adding DA, and a new absorption band appeared at 430 nm. This suggested the formation of new compounds such as the non-luminescent borate complex, which further supported the proposed static quenching mechanism.
